Assignment 06: Generalized Linear Models-Mixed Effects

Jason Edelkind

2023-10-14

Reading in Data

bat<-read.csv("..\\data\\bat.csv")

My dataset contains information from an experiment exploring whether fringe-lipped bats switch their targeted prey when presented with a new auditory cue mid-flight, and how both mid-flight prey switching and the distance between the new and old auditory cue influence attack accuracy, flight time, and capture success. For this assignment, I will be investigating the influence of secondary call treatment and prey switching on attack accuracy, using individual ID as a random effect.

Summarizing the Data

Linear Mixed Effects Model

There is a significant impact of both treatment and prey switching on location error, as well as the interaction of the two variables.

Unfortunately, there appears to be an interaction effect in my data. How does treatment type affect location error? Well, it depends on the treatment group and whether the bat switched prey or not. In treatment group S1 prey switching led to a decrease in location error, though the difference is not significant (12.1 cm,P=0.0554). In all other treatment groups, prey switching led to an increase in location error (S3: 12.2 cm,p=0.0357), in the case of groups SN and SS, a very large increase in location error (130.9 cm,p<0.001, and 151.8 cm,p<0.001 respectively).

This table looks at pairs within prey switch groups. In the No prey switch group, the following pairs are significantly different: S1/S3, S3/SS, SN/SS (P=0.0469,<0.001,0.001 respectively) and the following pairs are not significantly different: S1:SN, S1:SS, S3:SN (P=0.4090,0.5522,0.4101). In the Yes prey switch group, all treatments are significantly different from each other except for SN/SS (P=0.9971).

This is an overall summary table comparing all pairs of experimental combinations which reiterates what I just explained. So in summary, the presence and distance of a mid-flight secondary prey call on hunting bats does effect location error, and the type of effect depends on whether or not the bat switches to the new target mid-flight. When the secondary call is 1 meter away from the first call, prey switching reduces location error. In all other cases (secondary call is 3m away, secondary call is 0m away, no secondary call) prey switching increases location error.
